<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-01-20T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-01-20T03:00:00-05:00" n="231" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/94: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-01-20T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January 20,
                                        1927—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 20—9:05
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>54. Supplementing my 42, January 17, 7 p.m. It is suggested that the
                            Department advise all American mission boards to instruct by telegraph
                            their missionaries in South and Central China promptly to withdraw from
                            stations when directed to do so by American diplomatic or consular
                            officers, since experience has shown the difficulty of inducing our
                            nationals to heed the advice of Government officials in this
                            respect.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
